entries.femaleVariant: V, nice to see you.
[Sit] Sure.
Wouldn't mind one.
I'm good, thanks.
[Sit] No thanks.
Wanna take part in the ceremony.
Wanna take part in the ceremony, but... wanna do it the right way – in line with tradition.
Could help you with that.
<mothertongue l="mex" m="Oye" b="" a=". Sit, sit. You want a beer?"/>
[Drink]
Lemme help you.
<kiroshi l="mex" o="Salud." t="Cheers." b="" a=""/>
<kiroshi l="mex" o="No hay bronca." t="No problem." b="" a=""/>
Been better.
Hanging in there.
Been better, to tell you the truth.
Hangin' in there, somehow?
What is happening?
That night, when... when Jackie fell... Let's just say things haven't exactly been easy since.
entries.maleVariant: That night, when Jackie fell... Let's just say things haven't exactly been easy since.

entries.femaleVariant: <kiroshi l="mex" o="Yo sé cómo te sientes. Todos lo sabemos." t="I know how you feel. We all do." b="" a=""/>
Somehow.
<mothertongue l="mex" m="Nuestra casa es tu casa." b="You could have come over for dinner. " a=""/>
Hmm. But OK – we put it behind us, hm?
<mothertongue l="mex" m="mi niña." b="But your heart – it's in the right place, " a=""/>
entries.maleVariant: <mothertongue l="mex" m="mi niño." b="Mh, but your heart is in the right place, " a=""/>

entries.femaleVariant: Fff, don't worry, it's symbolic. Look for something in his garage. His past is all there.
His garage?
Jackie had a garage?
Eh, don't mention it, V. You have respect. I admire that.
He used it for his motorcycle, mostly. But not so long ago he moved in. You'll find something there, I'm sure.
Won't mind me digging through his stuff?
entries.maleVariant: You won't mind me digging through his stuff?

entries.femaleVariant: <mothertongue l="mex" m="No, mija." b="" a=". He's gone. And funerals are for the living, not the dead. <Rich color=\"MainColors.ActiveBlue\">Toma</>, take the key."/>
entries.maleVariant: <mothertongue l="mex" m="No, mijo." b="" a=" He's gone. And funerals are for the living, not the dead. <Rich color=\"MainColors.ActiveBlue\">Toma</>, take the key."/>

entries.femaleVariant: <kiroshi l="mex" o="Ahí te veo." t="See you." b="" a=""/>
A lot of time has passed. How you been?
I am in the middle of preparing an ofrenda. There is still so much to take care of...
<mothertongue l="mex" m="Gracias, mi cielo" b="" a=", but I will manage."/>
It's enough you come to say goodbye.
But somethin' I-I'd lay by his casket, that'd do justice to his memory – I... I don't got anything.
entries.maleVariant: But something I'd lay by his casket... That'd do justice to his memory, I – I don't got anything...

entries.femaleVariant: Mhm...?
Thanks, Mama Welles.
What's an ofrenda?
An ofrenda? Wh-what's that, exactly?
Hm, friends and family… we gather to celebrate the departed, our memories of them. And we bring things they loved in life and might need in the after.
Sure some beer'd be at the top of Jackie's list.
Heheheh. And there will be beer.
The garage is on Republic.
[Take key and stand] Thanks.
The pool table, we got to get rid of it.
Really…? It's pretty massive.
Maybe we scooch it, put it up against the wall?
Yes, it's me.
<mothertongue l="mex" m="sí" b="It's Montserrat Welles. The Coyote, " a="."/>
<kiroshi l="mex" o="Vamos, responde, carajo." t="C'mooon, answer." b="" a=""/>
Is me. I'm having an ofrenda for Jackie.
I call you many times. You don't answer, you don't call back…
I am having an ofrenda. I must send my son off.
Yes, consider yourself invited.
Mhm. See you then.
I need a special delivery.
Beer – an even dozen cases. Sure, yes, ten and two of the ginger stuff.
<mothertongue l="mex" m="Sí" b="" a=", lemons and limes to match."/>
Tequila… ayy, fuck it, a dozen cases too…
Hmm...
Uh-huh... You can't?
I see.
<kiroshi l="mex" o="Pfff. Bai." t="Pff. Bye." b="" a=""/>
Hrghh... One heavy... ugh... bastard.
Hrgh... argh, yeah... C'mon, chingado…
